image.altText: a man in a suit with the photo showing his side profile

props.synopsis: David Speirs has announced he intends to quit parliament and pause his Liberal party membership, with police saying he has also been charged. What does this mean for his future and the electorate he represents?

title.children: From SA Liberal leader to arrest, how did it all unfold?

image.altText: two smiling AFL footballers chatting after a game

props.synopsis: Thousands flocked to Port Lincoln over the weekend, for one of the state's biggest celebrations of Indigenous culture.

title.children: Eddie Betts and Tyson Stengle thrill crowds at SA's largest celebration of Indigenous footy culture

image.altText: A man wearing forensic overalls walks up to a house while another person in the same outfit is closer

props.synopsis: A post-mortem and forensic investigation following the discovery of a woman's body at a property at Mount Gambier on Saturday have determined the 52-year-old's cause of death to be non-suspicious, police say.

title.children: Death of 52yo woman deemed non-suspicious following post-mortem, police say

image.altText: Vineyards damaged by frost.

props.synopsis: As crop growers across the country's south-east come to grips with the fallout from last month's unseasonally freezing overnight temperatures, there are calls for the event to be treated as a natural disaster in order to trigger urgent government assistance.

title.children: 'Like a blowtorch': From above, the frost impact on vineyards is obvious

image.altText: An elderly man wearing a military hat and war medals.

props.synopsis: Glenn Dobie served Australia during World War II, but his friends and family later discovered he never received the recognition he was entitled to.

title.children: World War II veteran receives missing service medals nearly 80 years later

image.altText: Two go karts racing on a dirt track

props.synopsis: Racers and spectators flock to South Australia's south-east to compete in the Australian Dirt Kart Titles, with organisers saying the sport is a relatively affordable way to get into motor racing.

title.children: Australian Dirt Kart Titles organisers say sport is growing as grassroots introduction for juniors

image.altText: Pacific islander man in yellow high visibility jacket and grey beanie smiles at camera

props.synopsis: Kiribati workers came to Port Lincoln's tuna farms to fill workforce shortages and they've brought traditional fishing knowledge and songs with them.

title.children: With an affinity for the ocean, Kiribati fishermen feel at home on Australia's tuna farms

image.altText: The Israeli flag hanging from the frame of a house.

props.synopsis: One year ago, Hamas militants infiltrated Be'eri kibbutz. It was one of many coordinated attacks across Israel that began the Israel-Hamas war — and a delayed response by the Israeli defence force has been blamed for some of the 101 deaths, and dozens taken hostage.

title.children: 'Where the f*** were you?' One year on Be'eri residents want to know what happened to the IDF

image.altText: Smoke billows over a skyline

props.synopsis: The Israeli military says it launched a wave of artillery and air strikes on Hamas infrastructure in Gaza and Beirut's south to thwart what it said was an imminent attack. Follow live.

title.children: Fighting intensifies between Israel and Iran-backed militia on October 7 anniversary, with fresh strikes in Beirut and Gaza

image.altText: What remains of the refugee camp which is debris and dust. What appears to be a crater created from the blast.

props.synopsis: On October 7, 2023, Palestinians in Gaza were doing normal, everyday things, until their lives quickly turned upside down. One year later, we take a look at what happened inside Gaza through the lived experience of two Palestinians.

title.children: The war in Gaza has raged for a whole year. This is what it has been like for those who lived through it

image.altText: The flags of Iran and the United States of America behind a petrol pump.

props.synopsis: A day after oil prices surged, US President Joe Biden warned Israel against military strikes on Iran's oil export facilities for good reason — any attack could ignite another bout of inflation, and possibly plunge the world into recession.

image.altText: Yvonne Stretton sits with Dr Kean-Seng Lim in his office.

props.synopsis: Data from the Royal Australian College of GPs shows doctors are spending longer with patients but are worried about their financial viability as more patients either delay or avoid making appointments.

title.children: Good GPs are 'invisible' but this doctor uses maths to measure success

image.altText: Rows of milk cartons lined up in a shop fridge

title.children: 'There would be outrage': Shoppers confused and frustrated by shops with no prices

image.altText: Banking apps appear on a phone screen

image.altText: AntonioMichell-4

title.children: 'We have doctors driving rideshare': Government urged to streamline overseas qualification schemes

image.altText: Liam and Noel Gallagher of Oasis pose in jackets in front of a beige backdrop.

image.altText: Christos Tsiolkas crosses his arms and stands at a pool in front of signage declaring "deep water".

image.altText: A young woman smiling broadly and hugging another woman.

image.altText: Two men pick up award on stage

image.altText: The aircraft carrier USS Theodore Roosevelt departs Naval Base Guam

image.altText: A glass office building exterior reflects other buildings.

image.altText: gopro footage of a person walking over a deep pit

image.altText: Picture of dam wall in Toowoomba region.

image.altText: A woman reaches out to an alarm clock from bed.

props.synopsis: US stocks tumble into the red, while oil prices rise on Middle East conflict fears. Local stocks are tipped to dip at the open. Follow the day's events and insights from our business reporters on the ABC News live markets blog.

title.children: Wall Street loses 1 per cent, ASX to dip

props.synopsis: England secures a comfortable seven-wicket win over South Africa to move them a step closer to taking out the women's T20 World Cup.

title.children: England a step closer to T20 glory as South Africa counts the cost of dropped catches

image.altText: A headshot of a man in a suit.

image.altText: A close up image of a man with blond hair in a suit.

title.children: Donald Trump didn't want this film released before the US election — and it's been a lightning rod for controversy

image.altText: A large crowd holding signs and waving jewsih flags work through a Melbourne street.

image.altText: two men look down as the look through the wreckage of a city building

props.synopsis: In Beirut at night, you hear the constant low-level hum of Israeli drones. Sometimes, when it appears two or three drones hover over a target, the sound reaches a crescendo and a massive explosion often follows. Hezbollah is unable to shoot down any of these drones which present a round-the-clock threat.

title.children: The newest war in the Middle East is an asymmetric one — and Israel is winning

props.synopsis: Just four bears remain in contention for the title of beefiest bruin in this year's Fat Bear Week.
